## Will it create the strongest possible model?

**It is the best path among the three documents.** It is also the path I would choose if the goal is maximum final strength rather than quickest prototype.

The reason is simple: Hexo’s real move is a two-stone set. Sequential afterstate search is computationally tempting, but it makes the search assign credit to an artificial first-stone decision. Full exhaustive pair search has correct semantics but impossible branching. The final plan’s hybrid design keeps the true pair as the backed-up action while using factorized proposal and candidate-aware learning to make it trainable. That matches both the game structure and the external literature on sampled action planning. 

However, “strongest possible” depends on execution. The final plan will only outperform the sequential DAG baseline if candidate recall becomes excellent and pair scoring remains cheap enough at equal wall-clock. The plan knows this and makes it an acceptance criterion, which is good. It should not be treated as already proven.

---

## Will it lead to a complete full implementation with no compromises?

**Not by itself.** It will lead to a complete implementation **if** the missing contracts above are added and the phase gates are enforced.

Also, “no compromises” needs nuance. The final plan deliberately compromises on exhaustive optimality: it refuses to enumerate all legal pairs. That is the correct engineering compromise. It is uncompromising about **semantics**—the action is a completed unordered pair—but it is still an approximate sampled planner. So the honest answer is:

**The plan can lead to a complete, principled, full mainline implementation with no semantic compromises. It cannot and should not promise exhaustive no-compromise search over all pairs.**

That is the right tradeoff for this game.

---

## Final opinionated review

I would approve the final plan as the project’s mainline, with one condition: **do not start the large training run until the Gumbel/proposal/target contracts are made exact.**

The final plan’s core decisions are correct:

```text
exact Rust simulator
unordered pair macro-actions
sampled candidate admission
Gumbel root search
PUCT + progressive widening below root
global graph/window encoder
single + conditional proposal heads
symmetric biaffine pair reranker
candidate-aware targets
no unsampled-pair negatives
equal-wall-clock sequential DAG baseline
```

The biggest implementation risks are not “maybe pair actions are wrong.” The biggest risks are:

```text
candidate support collapse
biased sampled-set PUCT
raw visit-count target pollution
hidden all-pair scoring
D6 row identity bugs
terminal-equivalent winning pair noise
wall-clock underperformance
```

Fix those explicitly, and this is the strongest plan in the three-document set. Leave them implicit, and the project could still build a sophisticated system that trains on biased targets and loses to a simpler sequential DAG baseline at equal time.

